			<h3>VISUAL STORYTELLING</h3>
			<p>
				We talked earlier in the semester about the long history that narrative storytelling has. But for the majority of human history, narrative has been primarily a verbal medium. Literature and drama, narrative precursors to filmmaking, are heavily reliant on the spoken or written word. Filmmaking is unique among storytelling media (well, not unique, there are comics as well) in its ability to focus on exclusively visual material. Nevertheless, many films still rely heavily on the verbal communication of information, either in the form of spoken dialog, spoken voiceover, or text laid over the imagery onscreen. There are, however, some films that make an attempt to take advantage of the visual possibilities of cinema and communicate narrative information through visual rather than verbal means. For a good example of this, we need look no further than the above scene from <em>Old Joy</em> that we revisited earlier. Reichardt is trying to communicate to us that the characters are lost. A lazy way to very quickly dispense that information would be to have one of the character’s say “We’re lost.” Or perhaps, </br>
				“Do you know where we are?” </br>
				“Nope.” </br>
				Instead, though, she has one character giving directions while the other character asks if he’s sure. Although the direction-giver insists that he is, this first plants a doubt that perhaps the character giving directions doesn’t know where they’re going. Then that same character points ahead and says, “I remember that,” as if reassuring himself that they’re on the right path. We see that he is beginning to doubt his own sense of direction. Eventually we see several shots of the car turning around to go in the opposite direction. Now we know that they’re lost. This sequence has taken a bit longer than having a character say “We’re lost,” but it’s also made the viewer a more active part of the story, actively piecing the data together to come to her own conclusions. It’s a good fulfillment of the old writerly adage “Show, don’t tell”. 
			</p>
			<p>
				There is perhaps no better example of visual narrative storytelling in all of cinematic history than the film we’re watching this week: <em>2001: A Space Odyssey</em> by Stanley Kubrick. There’s no dialog of any kind for approximately the first and last half-hours of the film (2/3 the length of an average Hollywood movie). When there is dialog, it’s often sporadic, inconsequential or perfunctory. There are only a few dialog-heavy moments in which important information is distributed verbally to the viewer, and even these are occasionally nested inside layers of dense visual information.  
			</p>
			<p>
				Because the film relies so heavily on imagery to communicate information, this film does take more time to communicate that information than it would if it were relying on more visually lazy means. Occasionally, it moves at a pace that can at best be described as glacial. But even in those scenes, Kubrick’s slow progression serves to draw the viewer into the scene and allow the viewer to absorb and inhabit the moment. 
			</p>
